Part I - Used Cars Data Analysis¶

by Justice Inkoom¶

Introduction¶

An automotive corporation from India named XYZ wants to enter the country's used-car industry by establishing a local business to compete with its rivals. Since these may differ greatly from the market for new automobiles, they want to understand the factors influencing car pricing and sales. In essence, the company seeks to understand: What factors are important in determining the cost of a used car? How well such factors reflect a car's price The consulting company has compiled a sizable dataset of various makes and models of used automobiles available on the market based on several market surveys. The dataset includes the different variables that will be helpful during the analysis phase, Sales ID, name, year, selling price, kilometers traveled, state or province, region, fuel type, owner, mileage, engine, maximum power, and number of seats sold. The data was obtained from kaggle.com.

    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = cars_df, x=x, color = base_color)

    plt.title('{} by {}' .format(x,y))
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(x))
    plt.ylabel('{}'.format(y));

Insights from Univariate Exploration¶

  1. The data contains 2000 sold cars and 5906 unsold cars.

  2. Most of the used cars come from the central region.

  3. The seller type for most of the cars is individual owners.

  4. The descending order of the top three most appearing Car Brand name is Maurti, Hyundai and Mahindra.

  5. Most of the cars run on Diesel followed by Petrol (Fuel types).

  6. Most of the cars have a selling price between 0 and 2000000 (Rs). The selling price with most cars is 300000 (Rs).

  7. Most of the used car engine are between 1000 and 1500.

  8. Most of the cars have Manual transmission.

  9. Most cars has mileage between 10 and 20.

  10. Most of the cars are 5 seater cars.

The data contained no missing values nor duplicates so no cleaning was effected on it.

Due to the nature of the dataset I didn't clean and tidy data

Relationship between owner and sold¶

In [242]:
# define a function to help in determining the relationship between a variable and sold.
def let_relate(var1):
    plt.figure(figsize = [15,8])
    me = sb.countplot(data = cars_df,x = var1,hue ='sold')
    me.set_title(f'{var1} vs cars sold')
    me.set_xlabel(var1)
    me.set_ylabel('Count')
    for p in me.patches:
        me.annotate(f'\n{p.get_height()}', (p.get_x()+0.2, p.get_height()), ha='center', va='top', color='white', size=10)
    plt.show()
    
# plot the relationship between owner and sold
let_relate('owner')

Observation: First owner cars are more than any of the remaining owner type cars. The most sold cars are from first owner followed by second owner.

# define a function to find the relationship between two variables
def relationship_btw(var1, var2):
    plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])
    sb.regplot(data=cars_df, x=var1, y=var2)
    plt.xlabel(var1)
    plt.ylabel(var2)
    plt.title(f'{var1} against {var2}')

# plot a scatter diagram with trend line.
relationship_btw('mileage','selling_price')

Observation: Cars that have a higher selling price have a mileage between 10 and 30 with those between 10 and 20 having the highest price. There is a weak negative correlation between mileage and selling_price.

Relationship between Region and selling price¶

In [252]:
# create a function to plot box and violin plot
def box_violin(slot1):
    plt.figure(figsize = [15,5])
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    me = plt.gca() 
    me.ticklabel_format(useOffset=False, style='plain')
    sb.boxplot(data = cars_df,x = slot1,y = 'selling_price' );
    me.set_title(f'{slot1} vs Selling Price')
    me.set_xlabel(slot1)             
    me.set_ylabel('Selling Price (Rs)')
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    me = plt.gca() 
    me.ticklabel_format(useOffset=False, style='plain')
    sb.violinplot(data = cars_df,x = slot1,y = 'selling_price' );
    me.set_title(f'{slot1} vs Selling Price')
    me.set_xlabel(slot1)             
    me.set_ylabel('Selling Price (Rs)');

# plot a box and violin plot for region and selling price to determine their relationship
box_violin('Region')

Observation: This explains the importance of the Regions (East, Central, West, and South) in estimating the price of a car. It demonstrates that the east region had the highest selling price for automobiles; in this area, we can see the existence of an outlier that raises the price to the greatest level. The south region, which also has an outlier, was next.

Bivariate Exploration Insights¶

  1. Top three brand names with highest sum total of selling price of the cars are Maruti, Hyundai and BMW respectively. This means these brand names can be used to predict selling prices. The brand name with the highest number of sold cars also has the highest number of unsold cars. It is same for the second and third. The top three brand names in terms of sold and unsold number of cars are Maruti, Hyundai and Mahindra respectively.

  1. First owner cars have the highest selling price followed by second owner and third. First owner cars are more than any of the remaining owner type cars. The most sold cars are from first owner followed by second owner.

  2. Cars that have a higher selling price have a mileage between 10 and 30 with those between 10 and 20 having the highest price. There is a weak negative correlation between mileage and selling_price. Most of the sold and unsold cars fall between the mileage of 10 and 20.

  3. Manual transmission cars are often sold as compared to automatic. Manual also happen to the most in stock between the the two. Manual transmission cars have higher selling price than automatic transmission cars.

  4. There is a positive correlation between selling price and engine which means cars with higher. Most of the sold cars have engine size between 1000 and 2000. It is the same for unsold cars.

  5. Out of the number of sold cars, Diesel using cars has the highest number. This is also true for unsold cars. Diesel using cars have the highest selling price followed by Petrol using cars.

  6. The region with the highest sold number of cars is the East, followed by Central, West and South respectively. The region with the highest unsold number of cars is Central followed by West, East and South respectively. This explains the importance of the Regions (East, Central, West, and South) in estimating the price of a car. It demonstrates that the east region had the highest selling price for automobiles; in this area, we can see the existence of an outlier that raises the price to the greatest level. The south region, which also has an outlier, was next.

  7. Cars with 5 seats are more than cars with any number of seats. 5 seater cars are mostly sold followed by 7 seater cars. Four seater cars have a highest selling price.

  8. Year group 4, (2012 - 2017) and 5, (2018+) have all seller types with individual seller type topping the chart for all five year groups.

Relationship between Year, Selling price and Sold¶

In [258]:
# Define the function to determine multivariate relationship
def multi_plot(var1):
    plt.figure(figsize =(12,8))
    me = plt.gca()
    me.ticklabel_format(useOffset=False, style='plain')
    me.set_title(f'{var1} sold cars vs Selling Price')
    me.set_ylabel('Selling Price')             
    me.set_xlabel('year');
    sb.barplot(data = cars_df,x = var1,y = 'selling_price',hue ='sold',palette = 'plasma');

# plot a graph to display how year and sold affects selling price
multi_plot('year')

Observation: In the 1990's (first year group) the selling price for unsold cars exceeded that of sold cars. Also, this graph indicates that selling price increases with time (years).

Multivariate Exploration Insight¶

  1. Lexus turns out to have the highest selling price followed by BMW.

  2. In the 1990's (first year group), the selling price for unsold cars exceeded that of sold cars. Also, it was observed that selling price increases with time (years).

  3. South region has the highest selling price for used cars.

  4. Automatic cars have higher selling price than manual cars

Conclusions¶

  1. Among many features it was observed that Region, Name and Year are categories which affect buying and selling of car. Fuel feature does not affect buying and selling of car.

  2. Cars with high selling price are sold less compared to cars with low selling price. This is observed when Maruti, Hyundai which is the most sold car turned out to have a way lower selling price as compared to Lexus and BMW which had high selling price but are sold less.

  3. The number of seats in a car doesn't affect the selling price of a car.

  4. Selling price for both Manual and Automatic cars increase with time (years). Automatic is selling exponentially higher than Manual cars in year group 4 and 5.
